defaultQ 9. How should thedefault BBC be funded beyond 2016?default9.1
default              
defaultWe discussed four main possibilities: a) advertising
default revenue  
defaultb) subscription  
default   
defaultc)  TV licence fee  d) general taxation
default9.2
default              
defaultAdvertising was rejected for three reasons. Firstly, audiences appreciate a service without advert
defaultising and already complain about the amount of BBC on-air promotion. Secondly, the commercial imperatives of advertising would inevitably increase the pressure on programme makers always to appeal to the largest possible a
defaultudience, something we believe has 
defaultalready become
default detrimental to the BBC’s core public service broadcasting. Thirdly,
default 
defaultwe estimated that the amount of revenue needed to fund the BBC from advertising would begin to approach double the amount of advertising currently 
defaultin evidence
default (
defaultin the region
default of £4
defaultbn
default p.a.
default 
defaultfor television
default). The appearance of a giant such as the BBC 
defaultwould
default have a
default colossal impact on the
default market
default.
default9.3
default              
defaultSubscription was not favoured because the detail 
defaultwas hard to guess:
default 
defaultwhether
default individual service
defaults
default 
defaultwould 
defaultrequ
defaultire a separate subscription, 
defaulthow they might be bundled,  h
defaultow the orchestras and Proms 
defaultwould be funded (
defaultif added to a service like Radio 3 that would make it impossibly unattractive to subscribers
default)
default.
default9.4
default              
defaultThe licence fee has served the BBC well over the years but the inescapable fact is 
defaultthat it is an inherently regressive mechanism for raising funds, with the burden falling disproportionately on the poor
default/women
default who bear the brunt of 
defaultprosecutions,
default fines and ultimately imprisonment if they cannot pay the fines.
default9.5
default              
defaultOne considered benefit of the licence fee has been the link between the fee  paid and programmes watched, but this becomes a disadvantage as people increasingly use subscription services or commercial services only. The fee they pay is 
defaulttherefore 
defaultlinked to 
defaultBBC services which they do not use.
default9.6
default              
defaultFunding the BBC from general taxation has appeal: it is fair because
default it is
default  income-related; the mechanism for calculating and collecting the tax from individuals already exists; it avoids the need for – and expense o
defaultf – TV Licensing
default and its related responsibilities
default. 
